HW1 - Problem 12

    1. A valid density \(f(x)\) should satisfy two conditions: 1). \(f(x)\geq 0\) for all \(x\). 2). \(\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)dx=1\). [Reference: Lecture 2, slide 26/43 - “PDF”]

    • \(f(x)=\frac{1}{\Gamma(\alpha)}x^{\alpha-1}\exp(-x)\geq 0\) for \(x>0\).

    • \(\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)dx=\frac{1}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\int_0^{\infty}x^{\alpha-1}\exp(-x)=\frac{1}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\Gamma(\alpha)=1\).

    1. \(S(t)=1-F(t)\). Integrate the density from 0 to \(t\) to compute \(F(t)\): \(F(t) = \int_{-\infty}^tf(x)dx.\)

    1. This function is greater than 0. To show that it integrates to 1, we use the change of variable formula \(y=x/\beta\):
    • \(\int_0^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{\alpha}\Gamma(\alpha)}x^{\alpha-1}\exp(-x/\beta)=\frac{1}{\beta^{\alpha}\Gamma(\alpha)}\int_0^{\infty}(\beta y)^{\alpha-1}\exp(-y)\beta dy=1\).

    1. The dgamma() function returns the density of gamma distribution.
x <- seq(from = 0, to = 15, by = 0.01)
y1 <- dgamma(x, shape=1, scale=1)
y2 <- dgamma(x, shape=2, scale=1)
y3 <- dgamma(x, shape=3, scale=1)
y4 <- dgamma(x, shape=2, scale=2)
y5 <- dgamma(x, shape=2, scale=0.5)

plot(x, y1, main = "Gamma densities", xlab = "x", ylab = "Density", type = "l")
lines(x, y2, col=2)
lines(x, y3, col=3)
lines(x, y4, col=4)
lines(x, y5, col=5)

HW1 - Problem 13

    1. The function is nonnegative by definition. Use change of variable formula \(y=x^{\gamma}\), we have \(dy=\gamma x^{\gamma-1}\). Therefore
      \(\int_0^{\infty} \frac{\gamma}{\beta}x^{\gamma-1}\exp(-x^{\gamma}/\beta)dx=\int_0^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta}exp(-y/\beta)dy=-\exp(-y/\beta)\big|_0^{\infty}=1\).

    1. Similar to a.

    1. Solve the equation \(F(t)=0.5\). Note since \(S(t) = 1 - F(t)\), this equals solving \(S(t)=0.5\), and we already have \(S(t)\) from b.

HW1 - Problem 9

(a)

We can recover PDF from CDF via \(f ( x ) = F ^ { \prime } ( x )\).
\[\frac{d}{dx} \left(1 - \left( \frac { x _ { 0 } } { x } \right) ^ { \alpha } \right) = \frac{d}{dx} \left(1 - x_0^{\alpha} x ^{-\alpha} \right) = \alpha x_0^{\alpha} x ^{-\alpha-1}\] Hence \(f(x) = \alpha x_0^{\alpha} x ^{-\alpha-1}\) for \(x\geq x_0\) and \(0\) for \(x < x_0\).

(b)
## Function to compute CDF of Pareto
cdf <- function(x0, xs, alph){ 
  cd <- 1 - (x0/xs)^alph 
  cd[xs <= x0] <- 0 
  return(cd)
}

## Parameters and variables 
x0s <- c(1, 2, 5)
as <- c(0.1, 1, 10)
xs <- seq(0, 60, length = 1000)
dat <- expand.grid(x0 = x0s, alpha = as)
dat$lty <- rep(c("solid", "dashed", "dotted"), 3)
dat$col <- c(rep("green", 3), rep("red", 3), rep("blue", 3))

## Plot
plot(xs, rep(0, 1000), type = "n", ylim = c(0, 1),  xlab = "X", ylab = "Y")
for (irow in 1:nrow(dat)) {
  lines(xs, cdf(dat$x0[irow], xs, dat$alpha[irow]), 
        lty = dat$lty[irow], col = dat$col[irow])
}
legend(x = 30, y = 0.65, legend = c("alpha = 0.1", "alpha = 1", "alpha = 10",
      "x0 = 1", "x0 = 2", "x0 = 5"), col = c("green", "red", "blue", "black",
      "black", "black"), lty = c("solid", "solid", "solid", "solid", "dashed",
      "dotted"), cex = 0.8)

(c)

If \(u\) is a uniform random number on \([0,1]\), then \(x = F^{-1}(u)\) generates a random number \(x\) from any continuous distribution with the specified cdf \(F\).

\[ u \overset{set}{=} F ( x ) = 1 - \left( \frac { x _ { 0 } } { x } \right) ^ { \alpha } \] \[ \Rightarrow x = \frac { x _ { 0 } } { ( 1 - u ) ^ { \frac { 1 } { \alpha } } }\]

## Simulate uniform random number on [0,1]
set.seed(1)
u <- runif(100000)

## Let alpha = 0.5, x_0 = 10 
x_0 <- 10
alpha <- 0.5
x <- x_0/((1 - u)^(1/alpha))
x[x < x_0] <- NA
plt.df <- data.frame(x = x)

## Plot with ggplot2
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(plt.df) + 
   geom_histogram(aes(x = x),
                  bins = 200, fill = "yellow", color = "black") + 
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 661221.1)) +   ## limit X-axis
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 3500)) +       ## limit Y-axis
  labs(x = "X value (long tail not displayed)",
       title = "Histogram of generated Pareto variables, x_0 = 10, alpha = 0.5") + 
  theme_bw()

(d)

\[ S \left( x ; x _ { 0 } , \alpha \right) = 1 - F ( x ; x _ { 0 } , \alpha ) = \left( \frac { x _ { 0 } } { x } \right) ^ { \alpha } \] \[ S \left( 10;2,1 \right) = \left( \frac { 2 } { 10 } \right) ^ { 1 } = 0.2 \] Therefore 20% of the parts survive past \(10\) years with these parameters.

(e)

We denote \(x_{p}\) as the \(p\)-th quantile of the density. We solved for \(x\) in (c) and we have \[ x_{p} = \frac { x _ { 0 } } { ( 1 - p ) ^ { \frac { 1 } { \alpha } } } \] \[ x_{0.8} = \frac { 2} { ( 1 - 0.8 ) ^ { \frac { 1 } { 1} } } = \frac{2}{0.2} = 10 \] Interpretation as in (d): \(80\)-th percentile is 10 years, that is, 20% of the parts will survive past \(10\) years with these parameters.

HW1 - Problem 8

(a)

For all it holds \(x \in \mathbb{R}\), \(e^x > 0\), so we know that the function is positive. Let \(u = e^{−x}\). Then we have \(du = -e^{-x} dx\) and \[ \int _ { - \infty } ^ { \infty } \frac { e ^ { - x } } { \left( 1 + e ^ { - x } \right) ^ { 2 } } d x = \int _ { \infty } ^ { 0 } \frac { u } { ( 1 + u ) ^ { 2 } }\left( - \frac{1}{u}\right)du = \int _ { 0 } ^ { \infty } \frac { 1 } { ( 1 + u ) ^ { 2 } } d u \\ = - \left. \frac { 1 } { 1 + u } \right| _ { 0 } ^ { \infty } \\ = - \left. \frac { 1 } { 1 + e ^ { - x } } \right| _ { \infty } ^ { - \infty } \\ = \left. \frac { 1 } { 1 + e ^ { - x } } \right| _ { - \infty } ^ { \infty } \\ = \frac { 1 } { 1 + e ^ { - \infty } } - \frac { 1 } { 1 + e ^ { - (-\infty) } } \text{ (notation abuse)}\\ = \frac { 1 } { 1 + 0 } - \frac { 1 } { 1 + \infty } \text{ (notation abuse)}\\ = 1 - 0 = 1. \]

(b)

From above, we see that

\[ F ( y ) = \int _ { - \infty } ^ { y } \frac { e ^ { - x } } { \left( 1 + e ^ { - x } \right) ^ { 2 } } d x = \left. \frac { 1 } { 1 + e ^ { - x } } \right| _ { - \infty } ^ { y } = \frac { 1 } { 1 + e ^ { - y } } \]

(c)

\(F ( 0 ) = \frac { 1 } { 1 + e ^ { 0 } } = \frac { 1 } { 2 }\), therefore \(0\) is the median of the distribution. Therefore the median cancer risk is \(0\).

(d)

Recall from part (a) the cdf is given by \(F(x) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-x}}\).

To find the \(p\)th quantile, we want to find the value \(x\) such that \(F(x) = p\).

Solving for \(x\), we have \[\begin{align*} \frac{1}{1 + e^{-x}} = p &\implies 1 + e^{-x} = \frac{1}{p} \\ & \implies e^{-x} = \frac{1}{p} - 1 \\ & \implies e^{-x} = \frac{1-p}{p} \\ & \implies -x = \log \left( \frac{1-p}{p}\right) \\ &\implies x = - \log \left( \frac{1-p}{p}\right) \\ & \implies x = \log \left( \frac{p}{1-p}\right) \end{align*}\]

ggplot2 package

  • In R, basic plots can be made using base R functions (we used so far: hist(), plot(), qqnorm())

  • ggplot2 package allows to make more advanced plots:

    • multiple objects (i.e. multiple histograms),
    • multiple layers (point + line + shade + …),
    • customized plot labels (change font family, rotate labes),
    • multiple panel plots,
    • ploting map countours and marking points / lines / shapes on it,
    • much more (most beautiful ggplot).

ggplot2 plot data input: Data Frame

ggplot2 takes an input a Data Frame object (?data.frame).

  • A data frame can be thought of a table, or a two-dimensional structure in which each column contains values of one variable and each row contains one observation (observation := one set of values from each column).

  • Example: Data frame with 1 variable

# Simulate 1000 variables 
set.seed(123)
U = runif(1000, min = 0, max = 1)
X = rnorm(1000, mean = 0, sd = 1)

df1 <- data.frame(U)
dim(df1) # Get number of rows (observations), number of columns (variables)
## [1] 1000    1
head(df1) # Look up first few rows of Data frame
##           U
## 1 0.2875775
## 2 0.7883051
## 3 0.4089769
## 4 0.8830174
## 5 0.9404673
## 6 0.0455565
  • Example: Data frame with 2 variables

Operations on Data Frame

  • data.frame is a basic R structure for working with data tables

  • Plenty of operations one can do with data.frame object:

    • subset columns, subset rows
    • filter observations
    • mutate (construct and add new variables)
    • aggregate

  • dplyr is perhaps most popular package for data.frame operations. See package website https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/dplyr/ for references to tutorials (vignettes) on how to use dplyr

    _ Example: Introduction to dplyr

ggplot2 plot arguments. Example: histogram

  • ggplot() takes a data frame as the first argument and an aesthetic mapping (aes()) as the second argument.

  • Multiple layers and/or formatting function can be added to ggplot().

  • Example: Histogram of X variable values

#install.packages("ggplot2")
library(ggplot2)
plt1_base <- ggplot(df2, aes(x = X))
plt1_base + geom_histogram()

plt1_base + geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1)

plt1_base + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.2, color = "black", fill = "yellow") + 
  theme_minimal(base_size = 10) + 
  labs(x = "Values of X variable", y = "Count of values in the sample", 
       title = "Histogram of X variable values")

library(reshape2)
head(df2)

## 1 0.2875775 -0.60189285

## 3        U 0.4089769

## Use ggplot2 to plot mutiple histograms on the same plot
plt2_base <- ggplot(df2_long, aes(x = value))
plt2_base + 
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "blue", alpha = 0.3) + 
  labs(title = "2 variables (X,U) on one histogram")

plt2_base + 
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "blue", alpha = 0.3) + 
  facet_wrap(~ variable) + 
  labs(title = "2 variables (X,U) on one plot, separate histogram panels")

plt3_base <- ggplot(df2_long, aes(x = value, fill = variable))
plt3_base + geom_density(alpha = 0.2) + 
  labs(title = "2 variables (X,U) on one plot, density plots on one figure",
       fill = "Variable\nname")
